<p><a name="top"></a></p>
<h1>ESSUM23660 - Shares that may be awarded: Restrictions on eligible shares</h1>
<p>In the context of SIPs and Part 4 of Schedule 2, "eligible shares" means the shares that may be awarded to participants under the plan (paragraph 25(2)).  The use of the word “awarded” relates to free shares, partnership shares and matching shares only.  However, as dividend shares must be in the same company and of the same class, and carry the same rights, as the plan shares in respect of which the dividend is paid (paragraph 65), the requirements of Part 4 also apply to them. </p>
<p>The restrictions with which paragraph 30 is concerned are therefore those which may apply to the shares which a participant may acquire through the SIP. If such restrictions on eligible shares do not apply to all ordinary shares in the same company, paragraph 30(1)(a) will not be satisfied.</p>
<p>Examples of restrictions imposed on eligible shares by side agreements entered into by shareholders or option-holders, which are unacceptable unless they apply to all ordinary shares, are:</p>
<ul>
<li>restrictions on when the shares may be sold</li>
<li>restrictions on the person(s) to whom the shares may be sold</li>
<li>restrictions on the price at which the shares may be sold</li>
</ul>
<p>It is irrelevant that the shareholders agreement may have been entered into voluntarily, if its existence means that any shares the employee concerned may acquire through the SIP will be restricted in comparison to other ordinary shares in the company.</p>
<p>The existence of a “call option” which gives the holder the right to acquire an employee’s plan shares restricts the employee’s freedom to dispose of the shares for the purposes of paragraph 30.  The grant of a “put option” to employees, which entitles (but does not compel) them to require a person (e.g. the company or the trustees of an employee benefit trust) to purchase their shares, is unlikely to constitute a restriction under paragraph 30.  Such put options may, however, amount to an indirect restriction on plan shares if they are given to named individuals or non-employee shareholders only.  </p>
